\begin_layout Standard
The last line of the first reduction uses the fact that, for our usage,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\tau_{i}}^{\left(m\right)}=1$
\end_inset

 for all models and vertices.
 The last line of last two reductions uses the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{f}^{\left(m\right)}\delta_{f+1}^{\left(m\right)}=\delta_{f+1}^{\left(m\right)}$
\end_inset

; higher level facets are in the model iff lower level facets are in the
 model.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{m}w_{m}\delta_{f}^{\left(m\right)}$
\end_inset

 is the sum of weights over models in which facet 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 appears.
 If weights represent model probabilities, then this term represents the
 probability of facet 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{f}=\sum_{m}w_{m}\delta_{f}^{\left(m\right)}$
\end_inset

.
 We estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\tau_{ij}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\tau_{ijk}}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\tau_{ijkl}}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the class probabilities of individual vertices:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p_{\tau_{ijkl}} & = & \begin{cases}
1 & local\left(i,j,k,l\right)\\
p\left(S_{i}=O,S_{j}=O,S_{k}=O,S_{l}=O\right) & !local(i,j,k,l)
\end{cases}\\
p\left(S_{i}=O,S_{j}=O,S_{k}=O,S_{l}=O\right) & \approx & \prod_{x=i,j,k,l}p\left(S_{x}=O\right)\\
 & \approx & \min_{x=i,j,k,l}\left[p\left(S_{x}=O\right)\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

